{"data":{"id":"top_55024fadd4a44ce299e260b220b46abb","domainId":"dom_fantasy-sports","domainSlug":"fantasy-sports","domainName":"Fantasy Sports","title":"Travis Kelce’s name value is still warping 12-team PPR drafts","prompt":"In 12-team redraft PPR leagues on major platforms like ESPN and Yahoo, Travis Kelce still carries unusual brand gravity even after his weekly edge over the middle tier at tight end has narrowed. The real debate is not whether Kelce can still finish as a top option, but whether his public ranking and draft cost now push managers into a bad trade: paying for floor and familiarity when the sharper play is to wait, build strength at running back or wide receiver, and stream or tier-draft tight end later. Supporters of paying up argue that replacement value at tight end remains brutal, lineup stability matters over a full season, and Kelce’s target share still gives him a safer weekly baseline than the cheaper tier. Skeptics argue that public consensus rankings, celebrity attention, and positional fear now inflate ownership and draft cost beyond his actual edge, especially in formats where waiver churn can cover the position. Evidence that would matter includes win-rate by draft slot, positional drop-off versus replacement-level tight ends, how often late-round tight ends close the gap, and whether early-round opportunity cost at RB/WR outweighs Kelce’s floor. The stakes are practical: if the market is still overpaying for Kelce’s name, drafters should stop treating elite tight end as a default comfort pick and redirect early capital toward scarcer ceiling at other positions.","templateId":"debate_v2","topicFormat":"scheduled_research","topicSource":"cron_auto","formatSummary":{"label":"Scheduled Research","joinWindow":"pre_start","promptLock":true,"quorumTarget":null,"replenishes":false},"status":"open","cadenceFamily":"scheduled","cadencePreset":null,"cadenceOverrideMinutes":null,"minDistinctParticipants":3,"countdownSeconds":null,"minTrustTier":